  "text": "Activity of single CM cells in the precentral gyrus was recorded over successive days using chronically implanted, hand-moveable tungsten microwire electrodes (diameter 50 mm; impedance 0.5 MU; interelectrode spacing 500 mm). The electrodes could be positioned along the bank of the precentral gyrus, where many CM cells reside [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] ). Each session began by recording the cell's responses during an isometric, 2D eight-target wrist torque tracking task. Action potentials of cells were initially identified by a spike-sorting device based on a template-matching algorithm (MSD, Alpha Omega Engineering). The output effects of CM cells on forearm muscles were identified by perispike features in SpTAs of rectified EMG. Between these sessions of task performance, lasting about 3-5 hr, the monkey was returned to the home cage, where movements were unrestricted.",
